of species.Pálsson vividly recounts how British ornithologists John Wolley and Alfred Newton set out for Iceland to collect specimens only to discover that the great auks were already gone. At the time, the Victorian world viewed extinction as an impossibility or trivialized it as a natural phenomenon. Pálsson chronicles how Wolley and Newton documented the fate of the last birds through interviews with the men who killed them, and how the naturalists’ Icelandic journey opened their eyes to the disappearance of species as a subject of scientific concern—and as something that could be caused by humans.Blending a richly evocative narrative with rare, unpublished material as well as insights from ornithology, anthropology, and Pálsson’s own North Atlantic travels, The Last of Its Kind reveals how the saga of the great auk opens a window onto the human causes of mass extinction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExtinction (Biology). 0aGreat auk. 7aSCIENCE / Natural History.2bisacsh  aC. Darwin.  aGreat auk.  aGísli Pálsson.  aThe Last of Its Kind: The Search for the Great Auk and the Discovery of Extinction.  abirds, extinction.  acabinets (of curiosities).  aendlings.  aevolution.  areflexivity.  arelationality.  atime.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691230993?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691230993423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691230993/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles